ğŸ”¹ 1. What is Java?

Java is a high-level, object-oriented, platform-independent programming language developed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems and currently maintained by Oracle Corporation.

It follows the principle:
ğŸ‘‰ Write Once, Run Anywhere (WORA)

Because Java code compiles into bytecode, which runs on the JVM.

ğŸ”¹ 2. How Java Works 
Execution Flow:

.java file â†’ written by developer

javac compiler â†’ converts into .class (bytecode)

JVM executes bytecode

Why Platform Independent?

Because:

Bytecode runs on JVM

JVM is platform-dependent

Java program is platform-independent

ğŸ”¹ 3. JDK vs JRE vs JVM
Component	Purpose
JDK	Development kit (Compiler + JRE + Tools)
JRE	Runtime environment (JVM + Libraries)
JVM	Executes bytecode

ğŸ‘‰ JVM handles memory management, garbage collection, and execution.

ğŸ”¹ 4. Why Java is Fast?

Even though Java is not as fast as C++, it performs efficiently because:

âœ” JIT Compiler

Converts bytecode into native machine code

Optimizes frequently executed code (HotSpot optimization)

âœ” Garbage Collection

Automatic memory management

Removes unused objects

âœ” Multithreading

Executes multiple threads simultaneously

